<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-quadratic-identities-in-numerical-cases" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Quadratic Identities in Numerical Cases</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction>
            <p>
            <dl>
                <li>
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.0 Numbers and Algebra
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p>
                        1.3 Quadratic Expressions and Equations
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p>
                        Apply quadratic identities in numerical cases
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p>
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p>
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            </p>
            <p component="lesson-plan">
                <p> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand what quadratic identities are and recognize the three key identities: <m>(a+b)^2</m>, <m>(a-b)^2</m>, and <m>(a-b)(a+b)</m>.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Derive and apply quadratic identities to expand and factor quadratic expressions.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li>
                        <p>
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Use quadratic identities to simplify expressions and solve problems more efficiently.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
    </objectives>
    <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/quadratic-expressions-and-equations/quadratic-identities-in-numerical-cases.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/numbers-and-algebra/quadratic-expressions-and-equations/step-by-step-guide_quadratic-identities-in-numerical-cases.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 1: Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Grouping</title>
                <p>
                    Groups of at least 4
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    <alert>Part 1:</alert> Define and discuss the following key terms:
                    <ul>
                        <li>Quadratic identities</li>
                        <li>Difference of squares</li>
                        <li>Perfect squares</li>
                        <li>Factorization</li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Part 2:</alert> Copy and discuss the following identities:
                    <ol>
                        <li><m>(a+b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2</m></li>
                        <li><m>(a-b)^2 = a^2 - 2ab + b^2</m></li>
                        <li><m>(a-b)(a+b) = a^2 - b^2</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Discussion:</alert> Discuss shortcuts these identities provide and their real-world applications.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>What is an Identity?</alert> An identity is a statement <m>P = Q</m> where both sides contain variables and give the same value for all values of those variables.
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    The teacher circulates among groups, asking probing questions such as: <q>Can you verify the identity by expanding?</q>, <q>What pattern do you notice?</q>, <q>How is the difference of squares different from the perfect square identities?</q>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <activity>
        <introduction>
            <p>
                <alert>Work in groups Scenario</alert>: Imagine you are planning a new garden in your backyard. You want to create a rectangular vegetable patch that has an area of <m>48</m> <alert>square feet</alert>. You decide to set the length of the garden to be <alert>twice the width</alert>.
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Let <m>w</m> represent the width of the garden. If the length <m>l = 2w</m>, write an equation for the area <m>A = l \times w</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Subsitute <m>l = 2w</m> into the area equation. Show that it simplifies to <m>2w^2 = 48</m>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Solve for <m>w</m> to find the width, then calculate the length.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Verify your answer by checking that <m>l \times w = 48</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>
        <task>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    <term>Discussion</term>: Suppose you wanted a <alert>square</alert> garden instead, with a side length of <m>(x + 3)</m> metres. Discuss with your group how you would calculate the area without just multiplying the numbers directly.
                </p>
            </statement>
        </task>

    </activity>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 2: Structured Instruction</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    <alert>Three Essential Identities:</alert>
                </p>
                <table>
                    <tabular>
                        <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                            <cell>Identity</cell>
                            <cell>Name</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="minor">
                            <cell><m>(a+b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2</m></cell>
                            <cell>Perfect Square Sum</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="minor">
                            <cell><m>(a-b)^2 = a^2 - 2ab + b^2</m></cell>
                            <cell>Perfect Square Difference</cell>
                        </row>
                        <row bottom="minor">
                            <cell><m>(a+b)(a-b) = a^2 - b^2</m></cell>
                            <cell>Difference of Squares</cell>
                        </row>
                    </tabular>
                </table>
                <p>
                    <alert>Difference of Squares:</alert> <m>a^2 - b^2 = (a-b)(a+b)</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Perfect Square:</alert> <m>(a+b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2</m> (positive middle term), <m>(a-b)^2 = a^2 - 2ab + b^2</m> (negative middle term).
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>Common Misconception:</alert> <m>(a+b)^2 \neq a^2 + b^2</m>. You MUST include the <m>2ab</m> term!
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <insight>
        <p>
            <term>Quadratic Identities</term> are standard patterns that help us expand expressions or calculate large numbers mentally without using long multiplication.
        </p>
        <p>
            There are three main identities we use:
            <ol marker="1. ">
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Perfect Square (Sum):
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>(a+b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Perfect Square (Difference):
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>(a-b)^2 = a^2 - 2ab + b^2</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        Difference of Two Squares:
                    </p>
                    <p>
                        <m>(a+b)(a-b) = a^2 - b^2</m>
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
        <p>
            We can use these identities to solve numerical problems (like finding <m>103^2</m>) or to find areas in real-world problems.
        </p>
    </insight>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                Use a quadratic identity to calculate <m>103^2</m> without using a calculator.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                We can rewrite <m>103</m> as <m>(100 + 3)</m>.
                Using the identity <m>(a+b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    \begin{aligned} 103^2 \amp = (100 + 3)^2 \\ 
                    \amp = 100^2 + 2(100)(3) + 3^2 \\ 
                    \amp = 10,000 + 600 + 9 \\ 
                    \amp = \mathbf{10,609} \end{aligned}
                </m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A square garden has a side length of <m>(x+3)</m> metres. Find the area using a quadratic identity. If <m>x=5</m>, what is the area in square metres? 
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                The area of a square is given by <m>(\text{side})^2</m>.
                Using the identity <m>(a+b)^2 = a^2 + 2ab + b^2</m>:
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    \begin{aligned} \text{Area} \amp = (x+3)^2 \\ \amp = x^2 + 2(x)(3) + 3^2 \\ \amp = x^2 + 6x + 9 \end{aligned}
                </m>
            </p>
            <p>Now, substitute <m>x=5</m>:</p>
            <p>
                <m>
                    \begin{aligned} \text{Area} \amp = 5^2 + 6(5) + 9 \\ \amp = 25 + 30 + 9 \\ \amp = \mathbf{64 \text{ m}^2} \end{aligned}
                </m>
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 3: Practice and Application</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p>
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Learning Experience</title>
                <p>
                    <alert>Worked Example:</alert> Factor <m>x^2 - 16</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Step 1: Recognize this is a difference of squares: <m>a^2 = x^2 \Rightarrow a = x</m>, <m>b^2 = 16 \Rightarrow b = 4</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Step 2: Rewrite as <m>x^2 - 4^2</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    Step 3: Apply the identity: <m>(x - 4)(x + 4)</m>.
                </p>
                <p>
                    <alert>More Examples:</alert>
                    <ol>
                        <li><m>9y^2 - 25 = (3y)^2 - 5^2 = (3y - 5)(3y + 5)</m></li>
                        <li>Expand <m>(2x + 3)^2 = 4x^2 + 12x + 9</m></li>
                        <li><m>x^2 - 10x + 25 = (x - 5)^2</m></li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Teacher's Role</title>
                <p>
                    Emphasize pattern recognition when identifying which identity to apply.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <exercise xml:id="ex-quadratic-identities-area-model-for-numerical-squares">
                <!--<title></title>-->
        <stack label="stk-quadratic-identities-area-model-for-numerical-squares" source="stack/top/1-0-Numbers-Algebra/Quadratic-Expressions-and-Equations-1/Apply-quadratic-identities-in-numerical-cases/Quadratic-Identities---Area-Model-for-Numerical-Squares.xml"/>
    </exercise>
    <exercises xml:id="exercises-apply-quadratic-identities-in-numerical-cases">
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Use a quadratic identity to evaluate <m>202^2</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>40\,804</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    Calculate <m>63 \times 57</m> using the difference of squares identity.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>3\,591</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A rectangular field has dimensions <m>(x+5)</m> metres by <m>(x-5)</m> metres. Express the area using a quadratic identity. If <m>x=12</m>, find the area.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>119</m> m<m>^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
        <exercise>
            <statement>
                <p>
                    A square playground has a side length of <m>(y+7)</m> metres. Write the area as a quadratic expression and find the area when <m>y=3</m>.
                </p>
            </statement>
            <answer>
                <p>
                    <m>100</m> m<m>^2</m>
                </p>
            </answer>
        </exercise>
    </exercises>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Phase 4: Assessment / Exit Ticket</title>
        <dl>
            <li>
                <title>Questions</title>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>Factor using the difference of squares:
                            <ol marker="(a)">
                                <li><m>x^2 - 49</m></li>
                                <li><m>4a^2 - 9</m></li>
                                <li><m>25m^2 - 36n^2</m></li>
                            </ol></p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Expand:
                            <ol marker="(a)">
                                <li><m>(x + 7)^2</m></li>
                                <li><m>(3y - 2)^2</m></li>
                            </ol></p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Factor as a perfect square:
                            <ol marker="(a)">
                                <li><m>x^2 + 6x + 9</m></li>
                                <li><m>4y^2 - 20y + 25</m></li>
                            </ol></p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Which identity would you use for <m>49 - x^2</m>?</p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>A square garden has sides of length <m>(x + 5)</m> m. Write the expanded expression for the area.</p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
            <li>
                <title>Answer Key</title>
                <p>
                    <ol>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                            <ol marker="(a)">
                                <li><m>(x - 7)(x + 7)</m></li>
                                <li><m>(2a - 3)(2a + 3)</m></li>
                                <li><m>(5m - 6n)(5m + 6n)</m></li>
                            </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                            <ol marker="(a)">
                                <li><m>x^2 + 14x + 49</m></li>
                                <li><m>9y^2 - 12y + 4</m></li>
                            </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>
                            <ol marker="(a)">
                                <li><m>(x + 3)^2</m></li>
                                <li><m>(2y - 5)^2</m></li>
                            </ol>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p>Difference of squares: <m>49 - x^2 = 7^2 - x^2 = (7 - x)(7 + x)</m></p>
                        </li>
                        <li>
                            <p><m>x^2 + 10x + 25</m> square metres</p>
                        </li>
                    </ol>
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
    </axiom>

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>
        <table>
            <tabular>
                <row header="yes" bottom="medium">
                    <cell>Learner Level</cell>
                    <cell>Support / Activity</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Struggling Learners</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide identity reference cards for each of the three identities. Use color coding to highlight matching terms. Use numerical examples first (e.g., <m>5^2 - 3^2 = 16 = (5 - 3)(5 + 3) = 2 \times 8 = 16</m>). Pair with a peer for guided support.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>The core lesson activities as described above.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> 1) Factor <m>x^4 - 16</m> completely. 2) Prove that <m>(a+b)^2 - (a-b)^2 = 4ab</m>. 3) Calculate <m>51 \times 49</m> mentally using an identity. 4) Derive <m>(a+b+c)^2</m>.</line>
                        <line><alert>Solutions:</alert> 1) <m>x^4 - 16 = (x^2)^2 - 4^2 = (x^2 - 4)(x^2 + 4) = (x - 2)(x + 2)(x^2 + 4)</m>. 2) <m>(a+b)^2 - (a-b)^2 = (a^2 + 2ab + b^2) - (a^2 - 2ab + b^2) = 4ab</m>. 3) <m>51 \times 49 = (50 + 1)(50 - 1) = 50^2 - 1^2 = 2500 - 1 = 2499</m>. 4) <m>(a+b+c)^2 = a^2 + b^2 + c^2 + 2ab + 2bc + 2ac</m>.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx"/>
</subsubsection>